{"title_page": "Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt", "text_new": "[[File:Siula grande.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[fold (geology)|folded strata]] in [[Cordillera Huayhuash]] seen in picture form part of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt]]\nThe '''Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt''' ({{lang-es|faja corrida y plegada del Mara\u00f1\u00f3n}}) is a {{convert|1000|km|mi}} long, northwest-southeast trending belt of deformed rocks located in the [[Andes]] of central [[Peru]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2016/><ref name=Megard1984>{{cite journal | last1 = M\u00e9gard | first1 = F | year = 1984 | title = The Andean orogenic period and its major structures in central and northern Peru | url = | journal = Journal of the Geological Society | volume = 141 | issue = 5| pages = 893\u2013900 }}</ref> The formation of the belt defines the Incaic Phase of the [[Andean orogeny]].{{refn|name=A|group=note|The Incaic Phase is one of the main structural events in central Peru defined originally in a 1929 posthumous publication of [[Gustav Steinmann]] (1856\u20131929).<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez/>}}\n\nPrior to the deformation and uplift the rocks forming the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt constituted the fill of a marine [[back-arc basin]] that existed in the [[Mesozoic]] and was parallel to the present-day coast.<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2012/> The [[dip (geology)|west-dipping]] [[Chonta Fault]] existed as a [[normal fault]] within this basin and allowed continued basin subsidence and sediment accumulation in the Mesozoic.<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2014>{{cite journal|last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Holcombe|first2=Rodney J.|last3=Rosenbaum |first3=Gideon|date=2014|title=The persistence and role of basin structures on the 3D architecture of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n Fold-Thrust Belt, Peru|journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]]|volume=51|pages=45\u201358|doi=10.1016/j.jsames.2013.12.007|bibcode=2014JSAES..51...45S}}</ref> The onset of Andean orogeny first caused the basin to rise and dry up with [[red beds]] being deposited in its eastern part. Then the sedimentary basin was subject of a complete [[basin inversion]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2012>{{cite journal|last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Jacay|first2=Javier| last3=Holcombe|first3=Rodney J.|last4=Rosenbaum|first4=Gideon|date=2012|title=Stratigraphic variations across the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold-thrust belt, Peru: Implications for the basin architecture of the West Peruvian Trough|journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]]|volume=38|pages=147\u2013158|doi=10.1016/j.jsames.2012.06.006|bibcode=2012JSAES..38..147S}}</ref> During deformation Chonta Fault acted as a barrier \"damming-up\" [[fold (geology)|folded]] and [[thrust (geology)|thrusted]] strata west of it. This makes the fault define the limits of two different styles of [[thin-skinned deformation]] within the belt. The fault was reactivated as an [[inverse fault]] during basin inversion in the [[Eocene]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2014/>\n\n== Erosion, mineralization, intrusion and burial ==\nThe [[unconformity]] that cuts across the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt show the Incaic Phase of the [[Andean orogeny]] ended no later than 33 million years ago in the earliest [[Oligocene]]. Above this unconformity the belt is overlain by volcanic rocks of [[Late Eocene]] to [[Miocene]] age.<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez>{{cite journal |last=Pfiffner |first=Adrian O. |last2=Gonzalez |first2=Laura |date=2013 |title=Mesozoic\u2013Cenozoic Evolution of the Western Margin of South America: Case Study of the Peruvian Andes |url= |journal= Geosciences|volume=3 |issue= 2|pages=262\u2013310 |doi=10.3390/geosciences3020262|bibcode=2013Geosc...3..262P }}</ref> The parts of the belt are [[intrusion (geology)|intruded]] by [[pluton]]s of the [[Coastal Batholith of Peru]].<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez/> There are various mineralizations of [[base metal]]s and [[precious metal]]s in the belt, being particularly common along [[Chonta Fault]]. Most mineralizations are either of [[epithermal]], [[porphyry copper|porphyry]] or [[skarn]] type. The most common ore metals in the mineralizations of the belt are [[zinc]], [[copper]], [[gold]], [[lead]], [[tungsten]] and [[silver]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2016>{{cite journal |last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Konh|first2=Barry P.|last3=Holcombe|first3=Rodney J.|last4=Rosenbaum|first4=Gideon |date=2016 |title=Thermotectonic history of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n Fold\u2013Thrust Belt, Peru: Insights into mineralisation in an evolving orogen |url= |journal=[[tectonophysics (journal)|Tectonophysics]] |volume=667 |issue= |pages=16\u201336 |doi= 10.1016/j.tecto.2015.11.007|access-date= }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Andes}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geology of Peru]]\n[[Category:Geology of the Andes]]\n[[Category:Orogeny]]\n\n\n{{geology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Siula grande.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[fold (geology)|folded strata]] in [[Cordillera Huayhuash]] seen in picture form part of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt]]\nThe '''Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt''' ({{lang-es|faja corrida y plegada del Mara\u00f1\u00f3n}}) is a {{convert|1000|km|mi}} long, northwest-southeast trending belt of deformed rocks located in the [[Andes]] of central [[Peru]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2016/><ref name=Megard1984>M\u00e9gard, F. (1984). The Andean orogenic period and its major structures in central and northern Peru. ''Journal of the Geological Society'', 141(5), 893\u2013900.</ref> The formation of the belt defines the Incaic Phase of the [[Andean orogeny]].{{refn|name=A|group=note|The Incaic Phase is one of the main structural events in central Peru defined originally in a 1929 posthumous publication of [[Gustav Steinmann]] (1856\u20131929).<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez/>}}\n\nPrior to the deformation and uplift the rocks forming the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt constituted the fill of a marine [[back-arc basin]] that existed in the [[Mesozoic]] and was parallel to the present-day coast.<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2012/> The [[dip (geology)|west-dipping]] [[Chonta Fault]] existed as a [[normal fault]] within this basin and allowed continued basin subsidence and sediment accumulation in the Mesozoic.<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2014>{{cite journal|last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Holcombe|first2=Rodney J.|last3=Rosenbaum |first3=Gideon|date=2014|title=The persistence and role of basin structures on the 3D architecture of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n Fold-Thrust Belt, Peru|journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]]|volume=51|pages=45\u201358|doi=10.1016/j.jsames.2013.12.007|bibcode=2014JSAES..51...45S}}</ref> The onset of Andean orogeny first caused the basin to rise and dry up with [[red beds]] being deposited in its eastern part. Then the sedimentary basin was subject of a complete [[basin inversion]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2012>{{cite journal|last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Jacay|first2=Javier| last3=Holcombe|first3=Rodney J.|last4=Rosenbaum|first4=Gideon|date=2012|title=Stratigraphic variations across the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold-thrust belt, Peru: Implications for the basin architecture of the West Peruvian Trough|journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]]|volume=38|pages=147\u2013158|doi=10.1016/j.jsames.2012.06.006|bibcode=2012JSAES..38..147S}}</ref> During deformation Chonta Fault acted as a barrier \"damming-up\" [[fold (geology)|folded]] and [[thrust (geology)|thrusted]] strata west of it. This makes the fault define the limits of two different styles of [[thin-skinned deformation]] within the belt. The fault was reactivated as an [[inverse fault]] during basin inversion in the [[Eocene]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2014/>\n\n== Erosion, mineralization, intrusion and burial ==\nThe [[unconformity]] that cuts across the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n fold and thrust belt show the Incaic Phase of the [[Andean orogeny]] ended no later than 33 million years ago in the earliest [[Oligocene]]. Above this unconformity the belt is overlain by volcanic rocks of [[Late Eocene]] to [[Miocene]] age.<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez>{{cite journal |last=Pfiffner |first=Adrian O. |last2=Gonzalez |first2=Laura |date=2013 |title=Mesozoic\u2013Cenozoic Evolution of the Western Margin of South America: Case Study of the Peruvian Andes |url= |journal= Geosciences|volume=3 |issue= 2|pages=262\u2013310 |doi=10.3390/geosciences3020262|bibcode=2013Geosc...3..262P }}</ref> The parts of the belt are [[intrusion (geology)|intruded]] by [[pluton]]s of the [[Coastal Batholith of Peru]].<ref name=pfiffnergonzalez/> There are various mineralizations of [[base metal]]s and [[precious metal]]s in the belt, being particularly common along [[Chonta Fault]]. Most mineralizations are either of [[epithermal]], [[porphyry copper|porphyry]] or [[skarn]] type. The most common ore metals in the mineralizations of the belt are [[zinc]], [[copper]], [[gold]], [[lead]], [[tungsten]] and [[silver]].<ref name=Scherrenbergetal2016>{{cite journal |last=Scherrenberg|first=Arne F.|last2=Konh|first2=Barry P.|last3=Holcombe|first3=Rodney J.|last4=Rosenbaum|first4=Gideon |date=2016 |title=Thermotectonic history of the Mara\u00f1\u00f3n Fold\u2013Thrust Belt, Peru: Insights into mineralisation in an evolving orogen |url= |journal=[[tectonophysics (journal)|Tectonophysics]] |volume=667 |issue= |pages=16\u201336 |doi= 10.1016/j.tecto.2015.11.007|access-date= }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Andes}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geology of Peru]]\n[[Category:Geology of the Andes]]\n[[Category:Orogeny]]\n\n\n{{geology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mara%C3%B1%C3%B3n_fold_and_thrust_belt"}
